"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76427","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The data provided in the following table relates to females who applied for <br>asylum as the main asylum applicant between 2010 and 2013. Claimants who have <br>had more than one period of detention in the three financial years specified, <br>have been recorded under the latest period of detention. Cases represented in <br>this table are those that, at the latest case outcome, have been; granted <br>asylum, detained or refused and removed on or before 31st March 2014.<br><br>The figures quoted have been derived from management information and are <br>therefore provisional and subject to change. This information has not been <br>quality assured under National Statistics protocols, as such it should be <br>treated as provisional and subject to change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Year in which claim for asylum was raised.</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Granted Asylum</strong></p></td><td><p>2140</p></td><td><p>2285</p></td><td><p>2515</p></td><td><p>1715</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Detained</strong></p></td><td><p>487</p></td><td><p>630</p></td><td><p>834</p></td><td><p>1020</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Refused and Removed</strong></p></td><td><p>739</p></td><td><p>668</p></td><td><p>531</p></td><td><p>376</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-22T11:34:30.2578648Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76427/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76427/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-08","Asylum: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many women who have sought asylum in the UK in each year since 2010 have (a) been granted asylum, (b) been detained pending application and (c) been refused asylum and removed.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","204430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76428","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The data in this table refers to main, female claimants who have raised a claim <br>for asylum and been detained in the financial years 2011/2012, 2012/2013 and <br>2013/2014, and who have been detained either on or after the day that a claim <br>for asylum was raised. Claimants who have had more than one period of detention <br>are recorded under the latest period of detention.<br><br>The figures quoted have been derived from management information and are <br>therefore provisional and subject to change. This information has not been <br>quality assured under National Statistics protocols, as such it should be <br>treated as provisional and subject to change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year of Detention (financial year)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of Grants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/2012</p></td><td><p>35%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>34%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>27%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-22T11:45:51.0550122Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76428/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76428/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-08","Asylum: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of women who have been detained pending their asylum claims were subsequently granted asylum in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","204427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76429","Home Office","false","2014-07-10","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for the Home Department can confirm the information <br>relating to lost, and stolen, mobile phones, Blackberrys and laptops can be <br>found on the following link to the Home Office webpage on the Gov.UK website:</p><p><br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/306918<br>/2013_Annual_ICT_Losses.csv/preview</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td>January - December 2013</td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Device / Incident</strong></td><td><strong>TOTAL</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Lost Blackberrys / Mobile Phones</td><td>62</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Stolen Blackberrys / Mobile Phones</td><td>12</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Lost Laptops</td><td>3</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Stolen Laptops</td><td>5</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Lost Removable Media</td><td>1</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Stolen Removable Media</td><td>0</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Recovered Blackberrys / Mobiles</td><td>2</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Recovered Laptops</td><td>0</td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information is recorded and published under calendar year, information on items <br>lost and stolen for 2014 will be published in early 2015.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-10T14:12:59.8498838Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76429/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76429/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-08","ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many mobile telephones, BlackBerrys and laptops were lost by her Department in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","204474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76430","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>As our officers are multifunctional and work across both immigration and <br>customs functions at all ports, (air sea and rail) to meet demand for our <br>services, the information requested is not available.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-21T14:46:48.7389788Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76430/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76430/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-08","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was spent on immigration security at UK airports in 2013.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","204497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76431","Home Office","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>Information obtained from management data from Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) <br>indicates that passport applications which were work in progress at close of <br>business on 7 July 2014 stood at 508, 625. HMPO have been working to address <br>this year's significant increase in demand for passports. According to HMPO <br>data, work in progress as at close of business on 16 July was 450,340.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-17T14:38:30.0557403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76431/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76431/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76431/answer/previousversion/9741","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-08","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications were defined as work in progress on 7 July 2014.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","204442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76432","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-15","<p>The following response relates to items owned by the House of Commons, issued by the Parliamentary ICT Service that have been reported as lost. Items not supplied by Parliamentary ICT (such as those owned by individuals or third parties) are excluded.</p><p>No losses were reported during 2013; four phones, one laptop and no BlackBerrys have been reported as lost so far during 2014.</p><p> </p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-15T16:24:04.4431213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76432/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76432/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-08","ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, how many mobile telephones, BlackBerrys and laptops were lost by the House of Commons Commission in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","204475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76433","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-14","<p>Erskine May's <em>Parliamentary Practice</em> is published by Butterworths under an exclusive licence granted by the Trustees of the May Memorial Fund, registered charity 306057, who own the copyright to the work. I understand that the Trustees are considering under what financial arrangements it might be practicable to make a digital version of Erskine May available online.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-14T15:48:23.4663487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76433/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76433/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-08","Parliamentary Procedure: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, if he will take steps to make the latest edition of Erskine May's Parliamentary Practice available free of charge online.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","204435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76434","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-15","<p>The general practice of the Welsh Affairs Committee has been to ask those submitting written evidence in Welsh to provide an English translation. It appears that in the 1990s when written evidence was submitted to the Welsh Affairs Committee in the Welsh language only, translation was provided by the Welsh Office free of charge. The Clerk of the House has asked me to say that, in view of the representations by the hon. Member and others, he is happy to accept the point of principle that submissions should be accepted without an English translation, and that he has asked the Committee Office to work on the details.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-15T16:26:01.5550722Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76434/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76434/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-08","Welsh Affairs Select Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, if the House of Commons Commission will make available to the Welsh Affairs Committee funds to allow the hiring of Welsh translators to allow submissions to be provided without English translation.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","204522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76435","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Since February 2011, DFID has undertaken several visits to Gambella and to Gambellan refugees residing in Kenya and South Sudan. These visits have included discussions about allegations of abuse and forced movement in relation to the Commune Development Programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID, together with partners from the Development Assistance Group in Ethiopia (the ‘DAG'), is planning a further visit to Gambella later this year.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-14T16:52:12.4780837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76435/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76435/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Ethiopia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if officials in her Department will meet displaced people from the Gambella region of Ethiopia to discuss forcible removal and abuse in the Ethiopian government's villagisation programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","204545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76436","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Ministers and officials regularly discuss all aspects of the bilateral programme with the Government of Ethiopia.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-14T16:53:01.5512936Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76436/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76436/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Ethiopia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when she last discussed the villagisation programme with the government of Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","204549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76437","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-15","<p>The UK is playing a leading role in tackling violence against women and girls internationally. This includes supporting efforts to end Female Genital Mutilation and Child, Early and Forced Marriage, leading work on protecting women and girls from violence in humanitarian emergencies, and building the evidence on how to prevent violence before it starts through a £25 million research and innovation programme called ‘What Works to Prevent Violence'.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the hon. Member to my recent written ministerial statement of 3 July 2014, Column 62WS<strong>, </strong>which provides further details on what the UK is doing on this important area.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-15T16:37:04.7429845Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76437/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76437/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the UK plays a leading role in tackling violence against women and girls in the most disadvantaged parts of the globe; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","204529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76438","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>The methodology for monitoring the Government's spending on malaria is provided in Annex A of the UK's Framework for Results for malaria in the developing world.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures for estimated total malaria spend using the methodology set out in the Framework for Results are reproduced below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em>£ million</em></p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total malaria spend</p></td><td><p>193.7</p></td><td><p>306.2</p></td><td><p>252.8</p></td><td><p>312.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures for 2013/2014 are not yet publicly available.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-14T15:58:37.3545011Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76438/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76438/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Developing Countries: Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding has been committed to tackling malaria in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","204594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76439","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p>The UK Government is at the forefront of work to promote human rights around the world, and regularly criticises Governments which violates those rights. This includes working to end religious intolerance and persecution and we strongly condemn any alleged persecution and will continue to uphold the rights of citizens, regardless of faith, ethnicity or belief.</p><p>We only provide aid directly to governments where we are satisfied that they share our commitments to reduce poverty and respect human rights. Where we cannot provide aid directly to governments, we will find other ways to help poor people in those countries.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-14T16:04:09.6006289Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76439/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76439/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Developing Countries: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that the processes governing the allocation of UK development assistance gives cognisance to the escalation of persecution against Christians.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","204613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76440","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Two Palestinian-led masterplans covering three areas have been approved following engagement with the Israeli authorities. As a result, these communities are able to plan for and build the homes and infrastructure they need without fear of demolition. We continue to advocate for the approval of more masterplans.</p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Mr Alan Duncan",,"2014-07-14T16:05:05.7485974Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76440/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76440/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 18 June 2014, Official Report, column 644W, on infrastructure projects: Jordan Valley, what positive benefits for Palestinians living in Area C have resulted so far from her Department's engagement with Israel.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","204640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76441","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>DFID's records show the following items have been reported as lost or stolen within the requested period:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Items</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of items lost or stolen</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mobile telephones</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BlackBerrys</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Laptops</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-15T16:57:09.2399203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76441/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76441/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many mobile telephones, BlackBerrys and laptops were lost by her Department in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","204476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76442","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>DFID has not made plans to fund the Backpack Health Worker Team through our bilateral programme in Burma after our current funding commitments with them conclude. DFID continues to support the 3MDG Trust Fund in Burma which supports many local NGOs across Burma in health activities.</p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Mr Alan Duncan",,"2014-07-14T16:17:23.323514Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76442/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76442/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Burma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what financial support for the Backpack Health Worker Team programme in Burma her Department will provide in the next two years.","false","Biography information for Fiona O'Donnell","East Lothian","Fiona O'Donnell","204484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76443","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>DFID is funding The Border Consortium though a three year programme which started in November 2012. The UK is one of the largest donors to The Border Consortium.</p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Mr Alan Duncan",,"2014-07-14T15:55:58.4091031Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76443/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76443/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Burma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is providing additional funding to The Border Consortium to help reverse recent ration cuts for refugees from Burma in camps in Thailand which they supply.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ward","Bradford East","Mr David Ward","204439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76444","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>DFID does not track all companies and organisations subcontracted or given grants by multilateral partners, such as the World Bank. DFID's Development Tracker, on the gov.uk website, and the World Bank's website contain many details about procurement and the flow of funds for individual projects. We also publish, on the gov.uk website, our Statement of Priorities and Expectations for Suppliers which sets expectations for the use of subcontracted organisations.</p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Mr Alan Duncan",,"2014-07-14T15:57:38.2386358Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76444/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76444/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-08","Burma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which companies and organisations are subcontracted or given grants by the World Bank to carry out projects in Burma funded by British aid.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ward","Bradford East","Mr David Ward","204440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76445","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>Whilst crime is falling, offenders are now more likely to go to prison and for longer.</p><p> </p><p>The number and proportion of offenders sentenced to custodial sentences at Magistrates’ courts within Keighley and Bradford Local Justice Area(s) and</p><p>Bradford Crown Court from 2008 to 2013 can be viewed in the table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="8"><strong>The number and proportion of offenders sentenced to an immediate custodial sentence at Magistrates’ courts within Keighley and Bradford Local Justice Area(s)<sup>(1)</sup> and Bradford Crown Court<sup>(2)</sup> from 2008 to 2013<sup>(3)(4) </sup> </strong></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Magistrates' Court</td><td> </td><td>2008</td><td>2009</td><td>2010</td><td>2011</td><td>2012</td><td>2013</td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2">All Magistrates' Courts in Bradford and Keighley LJA</td><td>Number sentenced Immediate Custody<sup> </sup></td><td>404</td><td>287</td><td>385</td><td>344</td><td>389</td><td>400</td></tr><tr><td>Custody Rate<sup>(5)</sup></td><td>3.3</td><td>2.6</td><td>3.5</td><td>4.3</td><td>4.7</td><td>4.2</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Crown Court</td><td> </td><td>2008</td><td>2009</td><td>2010</td><td>2011</td><td>2012</td><td>2013</td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2">Bradford Crown Court</td><td>Number sentenced Immediate Custody<sup> </sup></td><td>951</td><td>982</td><td>1116</td><td>1193</td><td>887</td><td>846</td></tr><tr><td>Custody Rate<sup>(5)</sup></td><td>57.4</td><td>52.5</td><td>47.1</td><td>48.3</td><td>46.4</td><td>49.3</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Notes:</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="8">(1) As of 1st January 2012 Bradford LJA and Keighley LJA merged into Bradford and Keighley LJA.</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="8">(2) Figures specific to Bradford Crown Court</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="8">(3) The statistics relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences the principal offence is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="8">(4) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="8">(5) The proportion of persons sentenced who are sentenced to immediate custody.</td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T11:17:04.7383743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76445/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76445/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-08","Prison Sentences: Bradford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of all sentences handed down at (a) Keighly Magistrates' Court and (b) Bradford Crown Court in each year since 2008 were custodial sentences.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","204458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76446","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-15","<p /> <p>Prison Service Instruction 51/2011: Faith and Pastoral Care of Prisoners outlines the policy regarding prisoners’ access to religious dress and possession of religious artefacts: <a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2011" target="_blank">http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2011</a><em> </em></p><p>There is no national policy regarding the wearing of religious dress or artefacts while an individual is in contact with the Probation Service.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes",,"2014-10-15T11:50:04.7205498Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76446/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76446/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-08","Prisoners: Clothing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on the wearing of the (a) niqab and (b) burka during interaction with (i) probation and (ii) prison officers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","204453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76447","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-15","<p>Government has no plans to change legislation to bring in a register of employees that take their employer to a tribunal, or of private settlements.</p><p>Employment tribunals are independent judicial bodies and, in line with the principle of judicial independence, Government cannot comment on, or intervene in, the tribunal's handling of individual cases or any decisions made.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-07-15T15:49:50.7311707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76447/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/76447/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-08","Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish the names of people who have taken multiple cases against different employers to an employment tribunal.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","204454"
