"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66018","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-15","<p>The Defence Academy provides professional skills and knowledge courses to Defence personnel. The Defence Academy 2014 course prospectus can be found on the Academy's website (www.da.mod.uk). A copy of that report and the 2012-13 Training and Education Statistical Analysis have been placed in the Library of the House. <br>The cost of providing each individual course is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost. The Defence Academy total operating costs in FY 2013-14 was £130.617 million.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-15T16:08:46.5019292Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66018/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66018/answer","20140602_61246 Statistical Analysis Report_Full DAIS.pdf","20140602_61246 Statistical Analysis Report_Full DAIS.pdf","Defence Academy Training and Educational Academic ","Defence Academy Training and Educational Academic ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66018/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what professional development courses are made available to staff of his Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66019","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-08-04","<p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence engages the Treasury Solicitor to provide legal advice and advice counsel in cases that have been appealed to the Information Tribunal under the Freedom of Information Act.</p><p> </p><p>Departmental spend for this work is detailed in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Costs</p></td><td><p>£48,849.06</p></td><td><p>£11,524.17</p></td><td><p>£108,825.94</p></td><td><p>£49,450.45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Appeals</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Figures for earlier years are not readily available. Figures provided are for the number of appeals for which MOD was billed in each financial year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-08-04T10:14:32.399977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66019/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66019/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66019/answer/previousversion/10498","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-07","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department spent on legal fees in cases relating to the release of information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66020","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>This information could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Details of all Ministerial overseas travel is published on a quarterly basis.</p><p> </p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2014-07-22T17:03:23.8362378Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66020/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66020/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66020/answer/previousversion/10501","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-07","Air Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what occasions each Minister within his Department has taken domestic flights on official business since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66021","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-10","<p> </p><p>The community cadet forces and Combined Cadet Forces (CCFs) deliver different but complementary elements of the Ministry of Defence's youth engagement strategy. <br><br>Where the establishment of a new CCF unit under the Cadet Expansion Programme is proposed, there is an approval process involving the single Service cadet organisations and consideration is given on a case by case basis of any possible adverse affect on local community cadet force units.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-10T13:50:59.960176Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66021/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66021/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-07","Armed Forces: Cadets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2014, Official Report, column 221W, on Combined Cadet Force, if he will make an assessment of the effect of recruitment to existing community-based cadet forces.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","204145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66022","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-10","<p> </p><p>The following military units are based at Imphal Barracks:<br><br>Headquarters 1 (United Kingdom) Division Implementation Team (followed by Headquarters 1 (United Kingdom) Division in Summer 2015)<br>Headquarters 15 (North East) Brigade <br>Headquarters York Garrison<br>Army Welfare Services York<br>Equipment Care Inspection Team York<br>Support Command Educational Training Services Branch<br>3 Army Education Centre York<br>2nd Signal Regiment<br>1 Military Intelligence Battalion 12 Military Intelligence Company 221 Military Intelligence Section<br>Defence Business Services (Defence Vetting Agency) <br>Headquarters North Region Special Investigation Branch Royal Military police <br>Support Command Forward <br>Elements of Defence Infrastructure Organisation<br>Elements of Defence Equipment and Support<br><br>The information on the number of square metres each of these units occupies is not held in the format requested.<br><br>Apart from Headquarters 15 (North East) Brigade, which will disband by 31 December 2014, there are no current plans to close or move any of these units away from Imphal Barracks.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-10T13:44:52.3259548Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66022/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66022/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-07","Military Bases: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which military units and agencies are currently based at Imphal Barracks; how many square metres of accommodation they each occupy; whether his Department has any plans to close any of those units, or to move them away from Imphal Barracks; and if so which units are involved and what plans are under consideration.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Bayley","York Central","Hugh Bayley","204130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66023","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>There are currently no plans to move Headquarters 1 (United Kingdom) Armoured Division from Imphal Barracks once it has moved there from its current location in Germany.</p><p> </p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-15T15:44:32.6553166Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66023/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66023/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-07","Military Bases: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, in providing accommodation for HQ1 Division in York what assumption his Department has made about how long the Divisional HQ will remain at Imphal Barracks.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Bayley","York Central","Hugh Bayley","204129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66024","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-21","<p>The first round of city deals with the 8 largest cities in England were concluded in July 2012 with 18 further deals agreed with English Cities by July 2014. City deals are bespoke negotiations between Government and local places based on the opportunities of a particular place and with no specific budget.</p><p>The Chancellor announced in the Autumn Statement that the UK Government would negotiate a City Deal with Glasgow and the Clyde Valley and the Prime Minister announced Heads of Terms with Glasgow and the Clyde Valley on 4thJuly.</p><p>The Deputy Prime Minister has received no representations from Welsh cities about city deals.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","204119 ; 204121","2014-07-21T16:44:54.9223099Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66024/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66024/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-07","Local Government: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what representations or applications from Welsh cities to the City Deals Fund he has received.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","204122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66025","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-21","<p>The first round of city deals with the 8 largest cities in England were concluded in July 2012 with 18 further deals agreed with English Cities by July 2014. City deals are bespoke negotiations between Government and local places based on the opportunities of a particular place and with no specific budget.</p><p>The Chancellor announced in the Autumn Statement that the UK Government would negotiate a City Deal with Glasgow and the Clyde Valley and the Prime Minister announced Heads of Terms with Glasgow and the Clyde Valley on 4thJuly.</p><p>The Deputy Prime Minister has received no representations from Welsh cities about city deals.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","204121 ; 204122","2014-07-21T16:44:54.5472908Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66025/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66025/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-07","Local Government: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, which cities in Wales have been allocated money from the City Deals fund.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","204119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66026","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-07-21","<p>The first round of city deals with the 8 largest cities in England were concluded in July 2012 with 18 further deals agreed with English Cities by July 2014. City deals are bespoke negotiations between Government and local places based on the opportunities of a particular place and with no specific budget.</p><p>The Chancellor announced in the Autumn Statement that the UK Government would negotiate a City Deal with Glasgow and the Clyde Valley and the Prime Minister announced Heads of Terms with Glasgow and the Clyde Valley on 4thJuly.</p><p>The Deputy Prime Minister has received no representations from Welsh cities about city deals.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","204119 ; 204122","2014-07-21T16:44:54.8598261Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66026/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66026/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-07-07","Local Government: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, when the decision to extend City Deals funding beyond England was taken.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","204121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66027","Department for Education","false","2014-07-10","<p>Funding for provision for 16- to 19-year-olds in the next Parliament will be subject to the next spending round.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-07-10T14:44:19.1396165Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66027/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66027/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Sixth Form Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of an increase in the numbers of young people at school age on funding for provision for 16-18 year olds in each year of the next Parliament.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","204208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66028","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>Departmental policy is to maintain a Register of Interests for executive and non-executive board members. This information is available for inspection on request at any of the Departmental offices, as stated in our annual report and accounts.</p><p> </p><p>Details of directorships and other significant interests held by Ministers are set out in the Register of Members' Interests for MPs and the Register of Lords' Interests. Both registers can be found on the UK Parliament website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/standards-and-interests/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/standards-and-interests/</a></p><p> </p><p>The Department also discloses Related Party transactions – summarised totals of transactions between the Departmental Group and entities in which Departmental board members and Ministers hold a controlling position or significant business interest – in its Consolidated Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p>The most recent disclosures are held within Note 26 of this report: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275186/DFE_Group_Consolidated_12-13_ARA.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275186/DFE_Group_Consolidated_12-13_ARA.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","204190","2014-07-14T16:58:05.9224383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66028/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66028/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will make it his policy to regularly publish any (a) private equity, (b) private school business and (c) other business connections and interests of (i) current and (ii) former (A) senior public sector employees, (B) Ministers and politicans and (C) board members of his Department (1) promoting, (2) taking up board positions on and (3) involved in the running of academies and free schools; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","204189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66029","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>The Department for Education has published non-statutory guidance for academies wanting to change from a single academy trust to a multi academy trust. The Education Funding Agency (EFA), on behalf of the Secretary of State, requires confirmation from the academy trust that a consultation has been held before a decision on making the change is granted. The guidance also refers to the EFA's need to be satisfied that the local authority has also been consulted. The EFA will consider any reasonable objections to the proposed change before making its decision.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>If the requirements to consult as set out in the guidance are not met, the EFA considers whether the academy trust should be asked to comply with the consultation requirements before a decision on the change could be made, or whether there is good reason not to do so.</p><p><br></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-14T14:41:51.1242281Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66029/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66029/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what requirement there is to consult where an existing single academy trust wishes to become a multi-academy trust; what steps are taken when those requirements to consult are not met; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","204191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66030","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>Departmental policy is to maintain a Register of Interests for executive and non-executive board members. This information is available for inspection on request at any of the Departmental offices, as stated in our annual report and accounts.</p><p> </p><p>Details of directorships and other significant interests held by Ministers are set out in the Register of Members' Interests for MPs and the Register of Lords' Interests. Both registers can be found on the UK Parliament website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/standards-and-interests/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/standards-and-interests/</a></p><p> </p><p>The Department also discloses Related Party transactions – summarised totals of transactions between the Departmental Group and entities in which Departmental board members and Ministers hold a controlling position or significant business interest – in its Consolidated Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p>The most recent disclosures are held within Note 26 of this report: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275186/DFE_Group_Consolidated_12-13_ARA.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275186/DFE_Group_Consolidated_12-13_ARA.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","204189","2014-07-14T16:58:05.7661783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66030/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66030/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish any names his Department holds of (a) current and (b) former senior public employees and Ministers (i) promoting, (ii) taking up board positions on and (iii) involved in the running of academies and free schools; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","204190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66031","Department for Education","false","2014-07-11","<p>A full list of academies that were awarded an allocation through the latest round is published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/academies-capital-maintenance-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/academies-capital-maintenance-fund</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-11T15:48:43.3465643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66031/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66031/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66031/answer/previousversion/9534","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications were received from academies to expand to meet parental demand as part of Round 1 of the Academies Capital Maintenance Fund 2014-15; and how many such applications were approved.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Hoban","Fareham","Mr Mark Hoban","204264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66032","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department for Education aims is to publish both the key stage 4 (KS4) and key stage 5 (KS5) destination measures in performance tables once we are content that the data are robust enough. KS4 education destinations are already included in performance tables, and have been since 2013, but before we publish full destinations data we have to test and evaluate it fully to ensure reliability.</p><p> </p><p>We published the KS5 destination measure as experimental statistics in the 2014 destinations statistical first release[1] because of the inclusion of new institutions, such as independent schools and special schools, for the first time. The employment, training and characteristics data need to be fully tested and evaluated before they can be published on the performance tables website. Tables, including employment data and breakdowns of the data based on student characteristics for former KS4 students, have also been published in the destination measures' statistical first release (experimental statistics) alongside the KS5 data.</p><p> </p><p>[1] https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-destinations</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-14T14:37:58.6100135Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66032/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66032/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans his Department has to reform school performance measures to include destination data and include the number of school students who enter employment or work-based training.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Luff","Mid Worcestershire","Sir Peter Luff","204197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66033","Department for Education","false","2014-07-10","<p>Tables detailing the number of pupils eligible for the pupil premium in the financial year 2014-2015 at school and local authority level are available online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-2014-to-2015-illustrative-allocation-tables/%20" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/pupil-premium-2014-to-2015-illustrative-allocation-tables/ </a></p><p> </p><p>The tables show that 18.2% of secondary school pupils in Gloucestershire are eligible for the deprivation pupil premium in 2014-2015.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-10T16:44:35.0581094Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66033/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66033/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of secondary school students in Gloucestershire qualify for the pupil premium.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","204206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66034","Department for Education","false","2014-07-10","<p>We confirm final funding rates for 16-19 year olds in the spring before the start of each academic year. We confirmed rates for academic year 2014/15 in March 2014. We will confirm rates for 2015/16 in March 2015. Budgets beyond 2015/16 will not be agreed until after the Government's next spending review.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-10T16:43:06.3118549Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66034/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66034/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate his Department has made of the level of funding for each pupil aged 16 to 18 years old in each academic year until 2020.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","204202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66035","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department for Education does not hold a list of domestic flights taken by each Minister on official business. A list could only be compiled at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-14T16:52:07.1114063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66035/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66035/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Air Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, on what occasions each Minister within his Department has taken domestic flights on official business since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66036","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>Legal fees on cases relating to the release of information under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 are not held centrally by the Department for Education and the cost of determining these over the past five years would exceed the disproportionate limit.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-14T16:40:18.9971088Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66036/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66036/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much his Department spent on legal fees in cases relating to the release of information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66037","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department for Education's staff use the Civil Service Learning Portal to access development courses. The Portal currently offers 298 face-to-face courses, 217 <br>e-learning programmes and 6,000 learning resources.</p><p> </p><p>E-learning courses and learning resources are free to access. Costs for face-to-face courses are dependent on where the course takes place and the number of delegates.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-14T16:53:57.8674721Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66037/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66037/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what professional development courses are made available to staff of his Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66038","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>No senior civil servants appointed to positions in the Department for Education since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within the Department and (b) employed by a political party.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-14T16:51:43.5712423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66038/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66038/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many senior civil servants appointed to positions in his Department since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within that Department and (b) employed by a political party.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66039","Department for Education","false","2014-07-14","<p>The school food standards regulations apply for all schools, regardless of their religious status. We recently published new school food standards that will come into effect in January 2015. Alongside the standards, we have written a short guidance document for school cooks and caterers. This is published online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.schoolfoodplan.com/standards" target="_blank">www.schoolfoodplan.com/standards</a></p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-14T15:10:35.3400615Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66039/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66039/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-07","Faith Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance his Department has issued in relation to restrictions on types of food that may be served and consumed in publicly-funded faith schools.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","204358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66040","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-10","<p>The Department of Energy &amp; Climate Change (DECC) was created in October 2008. Since that date no political appointees who had been working in DECC have subsequently been appointed as Senior Civil Servants in DECC.</p><p>DECC does hold centrally any electronic records on the previous career history of its employees. To extract that information from paper files would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-10T15:27:50.0153496Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66040/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66040/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-07","Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many senior civil servants appointed to positions in his Department since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within that Department and (b) employed by a political party.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66041","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-15","<p>DECC would incur disproportionate costs in order to obtain the information.</p>","Kingston and Surbiton","Mr Edward Davey",,"2014-07-15T15:35:53.0770522Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66041/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66041/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what professional development courses are made available to staff of his Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66042","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-15","<p>Legal advice is not routinely sought on requests under the Act.</p><p> </p>","Kingston and Surbiton","Mr Edward Davey",,"2014-07-15T15:35:07.5450539Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66042/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66042/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-07","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much his Department spent on legal fees in cases relating to the release of information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66043","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-15","<p>The majority of domestic travel is by train. From time to time, Ministers take domestic flights where this is required by departmental business. The Department does not keep a central record of such visits, but all travel is taken in accordance with the Ministerial Code.</p><p> </p>","Kingston and Surbiton","Mr Edward Davey",,"2014-07-15T15:37:24.763036Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66043/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66043/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-07-07","Air Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, on what occasions each Minister within his Department has taken domestic flights on official business since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66044","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-10","<p> </p><p>This information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Details of all Ministerial overseas travel is published on a quarterly basis.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-07-10T14:26:45.2349183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66044/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66044/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Air Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on what occasions each Minister within his Department has taken domestic flights on official business since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66045","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>The Department does not hold the information requested.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-07-14T13:06:20.8495625Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66045/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66045/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much his Department spent on legal fees in cases relating to the release of information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66046","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-14","<p>This information is not held centrally and to gather it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-07-14T15:54:01.8356016Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66046/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66046/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what professional development courses are made available to staff of his Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66047","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-09","<p> </p><p>We do not collate this information centrally and to do so would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-07-09T14:26:45.2113955Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66047/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66047/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many senior civil servants appointed to positions in his Department since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within that Department and (b) employed by a political party.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66048","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-11","<p> </p><p>The Impact Assessment for the designation of the first tranche of Marine Conservation Zones assessed the economic benefits of Marine Protected Areas (MPAs). Marine Protected Areas are expected to result in increases in ecosystem services including provisioning (i.e. increased fish numbers), regulating (i.e. climate regulation), cultural and recreational services. Overall, networks are likely to have additional benefits, such as an increase in biological resilience to adapt to changed conditions. While it is not possible to fully monetise the economic benefits of MPAs the Government is continually reviewing and developing the evidence base in this area with a wide range of interested parties.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-11T16:01:07.9306357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66048/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66048/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Seas and Oceans: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the potential economic benefits of an ecologically coherent network of marine protected areas in UK waters.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","204171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66049","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-11","<p> </p><p>Defra supports increasing the seasonal production of fruit and vegetables through working with the sector, investing in new technology and research, and our sponsorship of the Horticulture Innovation Partnership</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since the recommendations by the Fruit and Vegetable Taskforce in 2010, the Government and industry have worked jointly to overcome barriers towards increasing the amount of indigenous fruit and vegetables produced. This has been despite the poor weather of 2012 and 2013.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-11T15:52:29.8024745Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66049/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66049/answer","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66049/answer/previousversion/9536","Biography information for George Eustice","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to encourage farmers to extend the seasonal production of fresh fruit and vegetables.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","204219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66050","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-11","<p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The UK's Marine Strategy Part One (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/marine-strategy-part-one-uk-initial-assessment-and-good-environmental-status" target="_blank">Marine strategy part one: UK initial assessment and good environmental status - Publications - GOV.UK</a>) assessed the cost of degradation of the UK's marine environment. It estimated benefits forgone in a range of £5 million to £50.6 million from the degradation of marine assets, although this was only a partial estimate. The Natural Capital Committee has already considered how natural capital concepts can be applied to the marine environment and Defra is considering its advice.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-11T16:04:50.3658032Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66050/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66050/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the economic cost of the degradation of natural capital in the UK's marine environment.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","204173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66051","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-11","<p> </p><p>A single figure would not give an accurate picture of the area of the UK's seabed that is protected from the practice of bottom trawling. This is due to the various fishing method restrictions used, including full spatial closures, seasonal closures and those based on the size of fishing vessels. Additionally, as Defra is only responsible for fisheries management for parts of the UK,with Inshore Fisheries and Conservation Authorities leading in the 0-6 nautical miles area, this data is not held in one place.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-11T15:56:48.1813186Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66051/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66051/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Seas and Oceans: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of the UK's seabed is protected from the fishing practice of bottom trawling.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","204165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66052","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Around 9.4% of the UK continental shelf, as defined by the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, Part V, Article 76, is designated as Marine Protected Areas (MPAs). This area includes all of the UK Exclusive Economic Zone.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The closure of fisheries in MPAs located in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland is a matter for their respective administrations. Therefore, information on the proportion of such areas in the UK is not readily available. As part of Defra's revised approach to fisheries management, 17 new byelaws have been introduced to protect vulnerable habitats from damaging bottom trawling activities in MPAs. Details of these byelaws, including the boundaries of closed areas, are available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- Cornwall Closed Area European Marine Site: <a href="http://www.cornwall-ifca.gov.uk/new_byelaw" target="_blank">http://www.cornwall-ifca.gov.uk/new_byelaw</a></p><p> </p><p>- Devon &amp; Severn mobile gear protection byelaw: <a href="http://www.devonandsevernifca.gov.uk/News" target="_blank">http://www.devonandsevernifca.gov.uk/News</a></p><p> </p><p>- Eastern European Marine Site byelaw: <a href="http://www.eastern-ifca.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=137&amp;Itemid=202" target="_blank">http://www.eastern-ifca.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=137&amp;Itemid=202</a></p><p> </p><p>- Isles of Scilly European Marine Site byelaw: <a href="http://www.scillyifca.gov.uk/European_Marine_Sites" target="_blank">http://www.scillyifca.gov.uk/European_Marine_Sites</a></p><p> </p><p>- Kent and Essex Bottom towed gear byelaw: <a href="http://www.kentandessex-ifca.gov.uk/i-want-to-find-out-about/regulations/keifca-byelaws/keifca-district-byelaws/" target="_blank">http://www.kentandessex-ifca.gov.uk/i-want-to-find-out-about/regulations/keifca-byelaws/keifca-district-byelaws/</a></p><p> </p><p>- North Eastern Humber Estuary European Marine Site byelaw: <a href="http://www.ne-ifca.gov.uk/legislation-and-byelaws/byelaw-regulations/" target="_blank">http://www.ne-ifca.gov.uk/legislation-and-byelaws/byelaw-regulations/</a></p><p> </p><p>- North Eastern Flamborough Head byelaw: <a href="http://www.ne-ifca.gov.uk/legislation-and-byelaws/byelaw-regulations/" target="_blank">http://www.ne-ifca.gov.uk/legislation-and-byelaws/byelaw-regulations/</a></p><p> </p><p>- North Western European Marine Site byelaw (named byelaw 6): <a href="http://www.nw-ifca.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.nw-ifca.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>- Northumberland mobile gear byelaw: <a href="http://www.nifca.gov.uk/byelaws/new-ems-byelaw/" target="_blank">http://www.nifca.gov.uk/byelaws/new-ems-byelaw/</a></p><p> </p><p>- Northumberland Seagrass protection byelaw: <a href="http://www.nifca.gov.uk/byelaws/new-ems-byelaw/" target="_blank">http://www.nifca.gov.uk/byelaws/new-ems-byelaw/</a></p><p> </p><p>- Southern Seagrass protection byelaw: <a href="http://www.southern-ifca.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.southern-ifca.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>- Southern Bottom towed gear byelaw: <a href="http://www.southern-ifca.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.southern-ifca.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>- Sussex Prohibition of fishing byelaw: <a href="http://www.sussex-ifca.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=143&amp;Itemid=205" target="_blank">http://www.sussex-ifca.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=143&amp;Itemid=205</a></p><p> </p><p>- Four new MMO byelaws linked below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/protecting/conservation/ems-byelaws.htm" target="_blank">http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/protecting/conservation/ems-byelaws.htm</a></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-14T12:05:46.6080524Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66052/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66052/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Seas and Oceans: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of the seabed within the UK's Exclusive Economic Zone is designated as marine protected areas; and what proportion of such areas exclude the fishing practice of bottom trawling.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","204168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66053","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-10","<p> </p><p>National Parks and Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty are well established national landscape designations that define areas with particular landscape qualities that merit protection. They are the jewels in the crown of our country's landscape and are given the strongest protection from damaging development.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Whilst Defra has no plans to introduce legislation to identify listed landscapes, English Heritage maintains a 'Register of Historic Parks and Gardens' which identifies over 1,600 sites assessed to be of national importance.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-10T10:32:27.5125762Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66053/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66053/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will introduce legislative proposals to enshrine the concept of a listed landscape.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","204222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66054","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-11","<p> </p><p>Defra's normal practice is to consult the Devolved Administrations in preparation for all Agriculture and Fisheries Council meetings. In this case the Northern Ireland Executive was consulted in advance on the briefing for all of the main agenda items.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive had the opportunity to see all of the briefing in advance, and their representative was present at the pre-Council briefing meetings.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-07-11T16:14:31.6745142Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66054/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66054/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","EU Agriculture and Fisheries Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his officials consulted their counterparts in the Northern Ireland Executive in preparation for the EU Agriculture and Fisheries Council on 16 and 17 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","204177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66055","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Changes in our bee and pollinator populations are due to a range of environmental pressures, including intensification of land use and loss of good quality habitat; pests and diseases; invasive species; use of pesticides; and climate change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2013 Defra's Chief Scientific Adviser, Professor Ian Boyd, commissioned a report on the ‘Status and Value of Pollinators and Pollination Services' to review the current evidence on the impact of environmental pressures on pollinators. A copy of this report will be placed in the House Library. We have just begun a two year project to develop a framework and test methods for monitoring pollinator abundance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the autumn we will publish our National Pollinator Strategy, which includes a series of policy actions to safeguard pollinators. In the meanwhile, we will continue to raise public awareness through the launch this July of our call to action, ‘Bees' Needs: Food and a Home'. This is a simple message for all land managers on the essential needs of pollinators and how to fulfil them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We want to see a thriving bee and pollinator population in the UK, to enhance biodiversity and support our food production.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","204118","2014-07-14T15:59:00.3601902Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66055/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66055/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the decline in the bee population; what steps he is taking to tackle such a decline; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","204117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66056","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Changes in our bee and pollinator populations are due to a range of environmental pressures, including intensification of land use and loss of good quality habitat; pests and diseases; invasive species; use of pesticides; and climate change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2013 Defra's Chief Scientific Adviser, Professor Ian Boyd, commissioned a report on the ‘Status and Value of Pollinators and Pollination Services' to review the current evidence on the impact of environmental pressures on pollinators. A copy of this report will be placed in the House Library. We have just begun a two year project to develop a framework and test methods for monitoring pollinator abundance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the autumn we will publish our National Pollinator Strategy, which includes a series of policy actions to safeguard pollinators. In the meanwhile, we will continue to raise public awareness through the launch this July of our call to action, ‘Bees' Needs: Food and a Home'. This is a simple message for all land managers on the essential needs of pollinators and how to fulfil them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We want to see a thriving bee and pollinator population in the UK, to enhance biodiversity and support our food production.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","204117","2014-07-14T15:59:00.4695706Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66056/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66056/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-07-07","Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will place in the Library a summary of his Department's Chief Scientific Adviser's latest analysis of the decline in the bee population.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","204118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66057","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-11","<p>The United Kingdom fully supports the Falkland Islands in the development of their economy. Attempts by Argentina to disrupt legitimate commercial activities in the Falklands have no basis in law. Threatening Argentine rhetoric and actions are formally challenged at high levels with the Argentine government in Buenos Aires and in international fora wherever and whenever it is necessary.</p><p>Despite Argentine efforts, the Falkland Islands economy is sustainable, continues to grow and has a positive future. The prospective hydrocarbons industry in the Falklands continues to attract interest from new international partners and will see further exploratory drilling next year.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-07-11T12:42:59.3917161Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66057/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66057/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Falkland Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to deal with Argentine threats to the commercial sustainability of the Falkland Islands.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","204128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66058","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>We have no evidence that Al-Shabab operate in Nigeria, however we are committed to working with the Nigerian authorities to tackle terrorism in Nigeria, including the abduction of young people by Boko Haram.</p><p>Following the abduction of the Chibok schoolgirls by Boko Haram in April, the Prime Minister offered a package of assistance to the Nigerian government. This included a pledge of £1 million to the UN's Safe Schools Initiative, which aims to protect children at school. DFID will also be working with US AID on a new education initiative to bring an additional 1 million children into education in northern Nigeria by 2020. DFID will also undertake further work through its existing education programmes to ensure that schools are safer in eight other northern states in Nigeria.</p><p>Following the Prime Minister's offer to Nigeria in May and the 12 June Nigeria Ministerial meeting in London, the Foreign Secretary announced new counter terrorism support for Nigeria in tackling Boko Haram. This includes tactical advice and training for the Nigerian military and support to regional intelligence sharing arrangements. Our support is being closely coordinated with that of international partners.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-07-14T14:47:52.3598794Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66058/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66058/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to assist the Nigerian government in combating Al-Shabab and prevent the kidnap of young people.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","204125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66059","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>During his visit to India in July 2014, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Richmond (Yorks) (Mr Hague) met with the Indian Foreign Minister Sushma Swaraj to discuss a wide range of issues, including civil nuclear cooperation. India welcomed the UK's strong support for their membership of the major export regimes, including the Nuclear Suppliers Group. There were no discussions on India joining the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-07-14T10:52:45.4259075Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66059/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66059/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he had on the prospects for India joining the nuclear non-proliferation treaty during his visit to that country in July 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","204112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66060","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-11","<p>We have made clear to the Burmese government that intimidation and threats towards humanitarian staff are unacceptable, and that it is the government's responsibility to ensure there is a secure environment for them to operate. The Burmese government must support humanitarian actors in their access and delivery of aid, freely and quickly, wherever it is needed most.</p><p>I personally summoned the Burmese Ambassador on 7 April and called on the Burmese Government (urgently)to restore humanitarian access to all communities in need and to ensure the security of humanitarian aid workers and all communities in Rakhine State. I last raised this issue with Deputy Foreign Minister U Thant Kyaw on 13 June.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-07-11T12:45:48.4370153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66060/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66060/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Burma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Burmese counterpart on ensuring the safety of foreign aid workers delivering essential assistance to displaced Rohingya Muslims in that country.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","204169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66061","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-10","<p>The African Court of Justice and Human Rights is not yet operational.</p><p>The UK continues to believe that there must be no impunity for genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity. We will continue to voice our support for this principle.</p><p>The UK strongly supports the International Criminal Court (ICC) as a court of last resort when other courts are unable or unwilling to act. The Rome Statute of the ICC states that the Statute shall apply equally to all persons without any distinction based on official capacity. This important principle supports the Court's work to end impunity for the perpetrators of atrocities and deliver justice for victims of such crimes.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-07-10T14:06:54.0451944Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66061/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66061/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will raise at the UN the Amendment to the Protocol on the Statute of the African Court of Justice and Human Rights adopted at the 23rd Ordinary Session of the African Union.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","204218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66062","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>There have been no senior civil servants appointed to the FCO since 2010, who were previously political appointees within the FCO or employed by a political party.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson",,"2014-07-14T08:04:01.0426743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66062/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66062/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many senior civil servants appointed to positions in his Department since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within that Department and (b) employed by a political party.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66063","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>Strengthening the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) as an institution is a priority under our 'Diplomatic Excellence' programme. Our staff are able to access a range of courses to continue their professional development. In 2013-14 staff undertook activities and qualifications in various fields including audit, accountancy, human resources, procurement, economics, communications, foreign languages, project and programme management, law, estate asset management and information management. Departments in London and posts overseas have devolved funds for learning and development activities. To obtain titles for all courses available and the cost of each opportunity taken can only be done at disproportionate cost.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson",,"2014-07-14T14:30:18.2735051Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66063/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66063/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what professional development courses are made available to staff of his Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66064","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>Since January 2013 FCO Ministers have made official domestic visits to the locations set out in the attached table.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-07-14T15:02:17.893479Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66064/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66064/answer","PQ204374 UK Visits Table.docx","PQ204374 UK Visits Table.docx","UK Visits Table ","UK Visits Table ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66064/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66064/answer/previousversion/9519","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 18 June 2014, Official Report, column 639W, on official visits, what domestic visits each of the Ministers of his Department has made since January 2013; and what the purpose of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","204374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66065","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-11","<p>We are unable to provide a reply as to do so would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-07-11T14:26:32.9936876Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66065/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66065/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on legal fees in cases relating to the release of information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66066","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-15","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office Ministers have taken domestic flights on 11 occasions since May 2010 on official business; the details are in the attached table.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-07-15T15:16:47.867","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66066/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66066/answer","Domestic flights FCO Ministers.docx","Domestic flights FCO Ministers.docx","Domestic flights taken by Ministers since May 2010","Domestic flights taken by Ministers since May 2010","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66066/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-07","Air Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, on what occasions each Minister within his Department has taken domestic flights on official business since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66067","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The available information is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Health (Mr Jeremy Hunt)</p><p> </p><p>- 24 February 2014 – London to Aberdeen and return flight.</p><p> </p><p>Former Minister of State (Mr Paul Burstow)</p><p> </p><p>- 3 January 2012 – London to Newquay.</p><p> </p><p>Minister of State (Norman Lamb)</p><p> </p><p>- 25 February 2014 - London to Newquay.</p><p> </p><p>- 26 February 2014 - Newquay to London.</p><p> </p><p>Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Dr Daniel Poulter)</p><p> </p><p>- 10 April 2014 – London to Newquay.</p><p> </p><p>To provide information for other former Ministers since 2010 would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T15:25:05.2646177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66067/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66067/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Air Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what occasions each Minister within his Department has taken domestic flights on official business since May 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66068","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>We do not hold information regarding the number of practices that have closed since May 2010.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-10T15:39:13.6996748Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66068/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66068/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many GP practices have closed since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","204309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66069","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>NHS Improving Quality has taken over the functions of NHS Diabetes and has no plans to establish a diabetes specific website. However, the archived NHS Diabetes website can still be viewed.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improving Quality has a number of programmes of work underway to reduce premature mortality from diabetes and improve the care of people with diabetes including:</p><p> </p><p>- Piloting new pathways of care to detect and manage asymptomatic coronary heart disease in patient groups with diabetic foot disease. The aim is to reduce premature mortality in this group of patients by 600 lives per year from 2015-16;</p><p> </p><p>- Supporting the NHS Health Check programme's ambition to achieve a 66% uptake rate within the eligible population for 2014-15. A key component of these checks is looking for risk factors for diabetes;</p><p> </p><p>- Supporting the implementation of the Cardiovascular Disease Outcomes Strategy;</p><p> </p><p>- Working to achieve patient centred, co-ordinated services for people living with long term conditions, including diabetes; and</p><p> </p><p>- Providing signposting and links to useful improvement resources relating to diabetes.</p><p> </p><p>More information on this work can be found on the NHS Improving Quality website at:</p><p> </p><p>www.nhsiq.nhs.uk</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-14T13:32:42.4485111Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66069/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66069/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will re-establish the NHS Diabetes website.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66070","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The decision to settle a dispute with an employee is an employment matter between the Trust and the employee.</p><p> </p><p>We have written to Sir Hugh Taylor, Interim Chair of The Christie NHS Foundation Trust, informing him of this enquiry. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","204258","2014-07-10T15:34:45.9657372Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66070/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66070/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Christie NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether a compromise agreement has been reached, or is in the process of being reached, with the currently suspended chief executive of the Christie NHS Foundation Trust on the termination of her employment.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","204260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66071","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Government has no plans to mandate local authorities to commission follow-up services following an NHS Health Check. It is for local authorities, supported by Public Health England, to work closely with their partners across the health care system, including through Health and wellbeing Boards, to ensure the different elements of the programme, including follow-up services link together. The Department, jointly with Public Health England, have issued guidance to support local authorities in delivering NHS Health Checks, including follow up services. NHS England is also producing an action plan to improve patient management following an NHS Health Check by March 2015.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","204230","2014-07-14T12:39:29.5414372Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66071/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66071/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Health: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to impose a duty on local authorities to commission follow-up services to the NHS Health Check.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66072","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The Secretary of State has been very clear that people working in the National Health Service should be supported to raise concerns. Trusts should have whistleblowing policies in place that are compliant with the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998.</p><p> </p><p>It is in the interests of patients and staff that trusts foster a culture where NHS workers feel confident that when concerns in the public interest are raised they will be heard. To that end, on 24 June, my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced that Sir Robert Francis QC, will lead an independent review of whistleblowing policies and practices in the NHS, which will consider what more can be done to further protect NHS workers who speak out in the public interest.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Secretary of State wrote on 5 March 2014 to all Chairs in NHS trusts and foundation trusts in England to reiterate the vital importance of fostering a culture of openness and transparency in the NHS in which concerns about care can be raised, investigated and acted upon.</p><p> </p><p>We have introduced a contractual right to raise concerns and issued guidance for NHS organisations. In March 2012, we strengthened the NHS Constitution to include an expectation that staff will raise their concerns early and a pledge that their employer will act upon those concerns.</p><p> </p><p>We are also introducing a Duty of Candour, so that when things go wrong, organisations have a statutory duty to admit mistakes and tell patients what has happened.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-10T15:40:21.9185055Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66072/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66072/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Christie NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that whistleblowers willing to give evidence on allegations of wrongdoing at the Christie NHS Foundation Trust will not be victimised or otherwise suffer detriment from the Trust for so giving evidence.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","204259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66073","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Government has no plans to mandate local authorities to commission follow-up services following an NHS Health Check. It is for local authorities, supported by Public Health England, to work closely with their partners across the health care system, including through Health and wellbeing Boards, to ensure the different elements of the programme, including follow-up services link together. The Department, jointly with Public Health England, have issued guidance to support local authorities in delivering NHS Health Checks, including follow up services. NHS England is also producing an action plan to improve patient management following an NHS Health Check by March 2015.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","204237","2014-07-14T12:39:29.4164205Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66073/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66073/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Health: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken to provide a separate follow-up service to the NHS Heath Check Programme.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66074","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The independent advisory group, the Health Premium Incentive Advisory Group (HPIAG), was set up as a sub-group of the Advisory Committee on Resource Allocation to advise Ministers on which indicators from the Public Health Outcome Framework (PHOF) would be suitable for inclusion in the Health Premium Incentive Scheme (HPIS). HPIAG developed a list of technical criteria to guide this assessment and reviewed all the indicators in the PHOF, including those indicators relevant to diabetes, against these criteria. HPIAG concluded that the diabetes related indicators did not meet the criteria and so would not be appropriate for inclusion in the HPIS. HPIAG's report showing which indicator met the criteria has been placed in the Library and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p>www.gov.uk/government/groups/health-premium-incentive-advisory-group</p><p> </p><p>The PHOF itself was subject to a full public consultation and the report of PHOF consultation has been placed in the library and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p>www.gov.uk/government/collections/public-health-outcomes-framework</p><p> </p><p>Ministers are currently considering options for introducing the scheme.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-14T13:28:38.3931594Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66074/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66074/answer","PQ204232 - Lib Doc - Report - Part 1.pdf ; PQ204232 - Lib Doc - Report - Part 2.pdf","PQ204232 - Lib Doc - Report - Part 1.pdf ; PQ204232 - Lib Doc - Report - Part 2.pdf","Part 1 ; Part 2","Part 1 ; Part 2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66074/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to include a diabetes-related indicator in the Health Premium Incentive scheme; if he will consult the diabetes community on the design of that scheme; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66075","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>In my Answer of 17 June 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, column 566W, I referred to the Prime Minister's Delivery Unit in error. My Answer should have referred to the Cabinet Office Implementation Unit.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that it reports centrally to the Cabinet Office Implementation Unit and is not aware of the named individuals within the Unit who receive its monthly reports on the Innovation, Health and Wealth programme.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:41:09.7348156Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66075/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66075/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, column 566W, on NHS: inovations, to whom in the Prime Minister's Delivery Unit the Innovation, Health and Wealth programme has been reporting during the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66076","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Pursuant to my answer of 17 June 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, columns 566-7W, I would like to clarify that overall policy for intellectual property rests with the Intellectual Property Office.</p><p> </p><p>Intellectual property as it affects health services rests with the Department of Health, within the portfolio of Will Cavendish in his capacity as Director General for Innovation, Growth, and Technology, working closely with other health service bodies, including NHS England, wherever relevant.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T16:29:22.7243031Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66076/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66076/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, columns 566-7W, on NHS: intellectual property, what the name and job title is of the official in NHS England responsible for the intellectual property strategy of the NHS; and what the name and job title is of that official's line-manager.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66077","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>We currently have no plans to do so.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","204841","2014-07-14T13:43:39.9553287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66077/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66077/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, column 566W, on NHS: innovation, if his Department will publish the sunset review of innovation and improvement bodies before the House rises for the summer recess.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66078","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>We understand that NHS England has not considered the effectiveness of an overall intellectual property strategy for the National Health Service. The work underway on the existing NHS intellectual property strategy as part of Innovation Health and Wealth is discrete and is looking solely at intellectual property from a commissioning and innovation perspective.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T16:31:35.6852661Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66078/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66078/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, columns 566-7W, on NHS: intellectual property, what data has been collected by NHS England on the effectiveness of the existing NHS intellectual property strategy to inform its review.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66079","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Figures taken from the Department's Business Management System categorised as spend on legal services from the Freedom of Information Team's central budget, show that £2,346.40 was spent in the 12 months between 1 April 2013 and 31 March 2014, and £22,627.71 in 2012-13. There was no spend in 2011-12, 2010-11 or 2009-10.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:18:32.9330824Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66079/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66079/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department spent on legal fees in cases relating to the release of information requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66080","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>Information on National Health Service expenditure on the treatment and prevention of obesity is not collected centrally. Decisions on spending are a matter for local NHS organisations.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to provide comprehensive information about the Department's expenditure on the treatment and prevention of obesity because a wide range of teams across the Department and other partners contribute to this policy. The Department has invested in a number of nationally-coordinated programmes which contribute to tackling obesity including the National Child Measurement Programme, Change4 Life, the School Games and Change4Life School Sports Clubs.</p><p> </p><p>We have also given local authorities ring-fenced funding of £5.4 billion over two years, 2013-14 and 2014-15, to help tackle public health issues including overweight and obesity.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-10T14:03:15.8873797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66080/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66080/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the level of (a) NHS expenditure and (b) other expenditure for which his Department is responsible has been for the (i) treatment and (ii) prevention of obesity in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","204313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66081","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The attached table shows a count of finished admission episodes (FAEs) for individuals who were admitted to hospital with a primary and secondary diagnosis of liver disease from 2009-10 to 2012-13.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-10T15:38:06.2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66081/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66081/answer","PQ204314_Berger_hosp_admissions_for_liver_disease(1).xlsx","PQ204314_Berger_hosp_admissions_for_liver_disease(1).xlsx","Liver Disease Hospital Admissions since 2010","Liver Disease Hospital Admissions since 2010","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66081/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Liver Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were admitted to hospital with a (a) primary and (b) secondary diagnosis of liver disease in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","204314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66082","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The National Cancer Intelligence Network (NCIN) part of Public Health England (PHE) now undertakes evaluation of the Be Clear on Cancer (BCOC) campaigns. For each campaign there is a defined set of metrics identified to evaluate the impact of BCOC campaigns. These include whether: campaigns are raising awareness of signs and symptoms of cancer; more people are going to their general practitioners with the symptoms promoted by the campaign; more people are being referred urgently for suspected cancer; there is an increase in diagnostic activity; there is evidence of a shift towards earlier stage disease and; of those referred urgently for suspected cancer, how many turn out to have that cancer.</p><p> </p><p>Within the last 12 months, PHE has run campaigns on five rarer cancers: the “blood in pee” campaign for bladder and kidney cancers (a national campaign following a successful regional pilot campaign); the “persistent bloating” campaign for ovarian cancer (regional pilot campaign) and, also as a regional pilot, the “persistent heartburn” campaign for oesophago-gastric cancer (oesophageal and stomach). The evaluation metrics for the campaigns were discussed, agreed and approved by the Public Awareness and Primary Care Steering Group chaired by NHS England's National Clinical Director for Cancer and which includes members representing PHE (PHE - Marketing and NCIN); NHS England, NHS Improving Quality; Cancer Research UK; Macmillan Cancer Support; Department of Health officials and other stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2014, Cancer Research UK prepared a BCOC evaluation update which is available on the BCOC website at:</p><p> </p><p>www.cancerresearchuk.org/cancer-info/spotcancerearly/naedi/beclearoncancer/background#evidenceandevaluation</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The update includes findings from the local oesophago-gastric, ovarian and regional “blood in pee” campaigns. The decision to repeat the national “blood in pee” campaign for bladder and kidney cancer in the autumn of 2014 is based on positive evidence from the evaluation of the regional campaign and encouraging initial evaluation results from the national campaign which ran from October - November 2013. These results demonstrated notable changes in symptom awareness and referral activity.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-10T15:30:11.0809291Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66082/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66082/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with Public Health England on progress made by the BeClear Campaign to improve the detection of rare cancers over the last (a) six months and (b) year.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","204310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66083","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) advises Ministers and the National Health Service in all four countries about all aspects of screening policy and supports implementation.</p><p> </p><p>The UK NSC has reviewed the evidence for screening for osteoporosis in postmenopausal women and recommended that screening should not be offered. The UK NSC will review the evidence for screening again in 2016-17 as part of its three yearly review policy cycle.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>A preferred approach is to target higher risk groups (post-menopausal women, those on long term steroid use and after a first fracture). Prevention, assessment and treatment is covered in National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence guidelines as follows:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://pathways.nice.org.uk/pathways/osteoporosis" target="_blank">http://pathways.nice.org.uk/pathways/osteoporosis</a></p><p> </p><p>www.nice.org.uk/guidance/TA160</p><p> </p><p>www.nice.org.uk/guidance/TA161</p><p> </p><p>www.nice.org.uk/guidance/CG146</p><p> </p><p>There is patient information on the management of and living with osteoporosis on the NHS Choices website:</p><p> </p><p>www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Osteoporosis/Pages/Introduction.aspx</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-10T13:59:13.3072522Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66083/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66083/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Osteoporosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of NHS trusts offer a screening programme of osteoporosis to reduce falls and fractures.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","204311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66084","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>Information on the number of people diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) clinical guideline <em>Rheumatoid arthritis: The management of rheumatoid arthritis in adults</em>, published in 2009, recommends that people with RA have a comprehensive annual review that is coordinated by the rheumatology service. The NICE RA Quality Standard, published in 2013, also includes the provision of an annual review as one of the seven quality statements that define high quality RA care.</p><p> </p><p>The 2013-14 Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) added new performance indicators on RA care, including ‘the proportion of people with RA diagnosed more than 1 year ago whose last comprehensive review was within 12 months of the previous review.'</p><p> </p><p>The QOF is a voluntary incentive scheme that provides additional reward to general practitioner practices for how well they care for patients based on performance against a number of agreed indicators. The report of the results of the 2013-14 QOF is expected for publication in autumn this year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-10T14:13:00.8660221Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66084/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66084/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Arthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of patients diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis received an annual review in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","204312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66085","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Innovation, Health and Wealth Implementation Board met on:</p><p> </p><p>2 July 2013</p><p>16 August 2013</p><p>30 September 2013</p><p>5 November 2013</p><p>3 December 2013</p><p>13January 2014</p><p>17 February 2014</p><p>24 March 2014</p><p>28 April 2014</p><p> </p><p>There were no meetings in May and June 2014 and the next meeting is scheduled for 8 September 2014.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has been conducting a ‘refresh' of the Innovation Health and Wealth programme to reflect on progress made, identify what more needs to be done and ensure that the programme continues to fit with the new health services landscape. We understand that NHS England plans to publish the outcomes from this process later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T16:30:18.1814377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66085/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66085/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, column 566W, on NHS: innovation, when the Innovation, Health and Wealth Implementation Board has met during the last 12 months; what assessment he has made of progress on the Innovation, Health and Wealth programme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66086","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department provides a range of development courses for all staff via Civil Service Learning, the recognised supplier for all training. The options predominantly fall under the main categories of Core Skills, Leadership and Management, Working in the Civil Service and Talent, as well as a range of training across a number of professions e.g. statisticians, Human Resources etc.</p><p> </p><p>Full details of all training activities and exercises engaged in by staff are not held centrally. Some activities are arranged individually or locally. For us to contact each member of the Department's local business teams to obtain such information would entail contacting a large number of staff and asking them to search for and retrieve such data. Therefore, while the Department does hold some information relevant to the hon. Member's request, extracting the totality of this data would require a significant amount of manual searching which would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:11:38.3485575Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66086/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66086/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what professional development courses are made available to staff of his Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66087","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department does not keep a central record of its officials' previous employment, but is not aware of any senior civil servants appointed, since 2010, who were previously political appointees within the Department or employed by a political party.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:14:04.6084172Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66087/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66087/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many senior civil servants appointed to positions in his Department since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within that Department and (b) employed by a political party.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66088","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>Rehabilitation services, specifically speech and language therapy, provide much of the National Health Service support for people with aphasia. As clinical commissioning groups are responsible for commissioning these services, they should be taking steps to ensure that support for people with aphasia is available and improve these services where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>More generally, NHS England is currently reviewing the provision of rehabilitation services. It works in partnership with charities which provide invaluable support for people with aphasia and is also working with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence on the development of generic rehabilitation guidance which will encompass speech and language therapy.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, as stroke is a significant cause of aphasia, the cardiovascular disease Strategic Clinical Networks are working with commissioners and providers to improve stroke rehabilitation services, including speech and language therapy after stroke.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-10T14:15:06.6944281Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66088/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66088/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Aphasia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve support for people with aphasia.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","204363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66089","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The National Health Service does not usually provide financial assistance to NHS staff who have to drive or take public transport to work.</p><p> </p><p>The reimbursement of excess travelling costs when employees are required to change their base of work as a result of a reorganisation or merger of NHS employers or when employees accept another post as an alternative to redundancy will be for local determination between employers and staff representatives.</p><p> </p><p>NHS employers only reimburse travel costs if employees make journeys in the performance of their duties e.g. to provide care in a patient's home.</p><p> </p><p>A number of trusts operate salary sacrifice schemes in respect of car parking, bikes for work, bus passes and car lease. Under a salary sacrifice scheme, an employee agrees to a contract variation to give up a proportion of their salary in exchange for a benefit.</p><p> </p><p>Some of the NHS organisations offer free shuttle services from train stations and between sites for patients, visitors and staff.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:07:44.2627628Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66089/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66089/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Health Professions: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what financial assistance the NHS provides to NHS staff who have to (a) drive and (b) take public transport to work.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","204359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66090","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Healthcare UK informs us that Howard Lyons, Managing Director, met with a delegation from the Northern Ireland Executive at an event in Brazil in May 2013, including Arlene Foster MLA, Minister for Enterprise Trade and Investment in the Northern Ireland Legislative Assembly.</p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-14T14:49:32.3953359Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66090/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66090/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Healthcare UK: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the Chief Executive of Healthcare UK has met with officials from the Northern Ireland Executive to promote his organisation's work in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","204195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66091","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>None. My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health has not held any discussions with his Ministerial counterpart in the Northern Ireland Executive on promoting in Northern Ireland the support and services offered to healthcare providers by Healthcare UK.</p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-14T14:47:30.461859Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66091/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66091/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Healthcare UK: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his Ministerial counterpart in the Northern Ireland Executive on promoting in Northern Ireland the support and services offered to healthcare providers by Healthcare UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","204196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66092","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>It is a matter of public record thatthese issues fell within the portfolio of the then Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Health (the Rt. hon. the Lord Darzi of Denham KBE).</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T16:53:35.0571Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66092/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66092/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which Minister in his Department approved the transfer of commissioning responsibility for NHS Innovations hubs from the NHS Institute for Innovation and Improvement to strategic health authorities in 2009.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66093","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Healthcare UK informs us that they have provided support to a Northern Irish digital healthcare company to progress contract negotiations with a Chinese partner. At the request of the company two Healthcare UK officials travelled to Belfast to meet with the company directors in order to understand the project and the support required from Healthcare UK. A second trip occurred soon after, again at the request of the company, to offer United Kingdom government support in the presence of the Chinese partners who were visiting Northern Ireland at the time. The Northern Irish company has expressed thanks for the support that they required from Healthcare UK in addition to what they have received from Invest Northern Ireland and Northern Ireland's Health Minister, Mr E Poots. Healthcare UK has also provided advice to the Office of the First Minister and the Deputy First Minister on their overseas engagement.</p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-14T14:58:19.8425358Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66093/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66093/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Healthcare UK: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent work Healthcare UK has done to encourage healthcare providers in Northern Ireland to work with their British counterparts on bidding for overseas projects.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","204194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66094","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published public health guidance on lifestyle weight management services in May 2014 which recommends the use of weight management programmes where certain criteria apply.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence considered by NICE is published alongside its guidance. Further information can be found at:</p><p> </p><p>www.nice.org.uk/Guidance/PH53</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-14T09:55:28.1846463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66094/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66094/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what evidence was (a) received and (b) commissioned by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence prior to its recommendation to recommend the commissioning of branded weight loss programmes by NHS agencies.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","204140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66095","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department and Public Health England (PHE) have not made a direct assessment of the efficacy and cost-effectiveness of branded weight management programmes.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and PHE supports theNational Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) public health guidance on ‘Managing overweight and obesity in adults – lifestyle weight management services', which makes recommendations on the provision of effective multi-component lifestyle weight management services for adults who are overweight or obese. This includes the recommendations that the commissioning of such services is based on the effectiveness of the programme as outlined in the NICE guidance.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","204138","2014-07-14T09:45:43.2882291Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66095/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66095/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of branded weight loss programmes in achieving healthy and sustainable weight loss.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","204139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66096","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>We understand that the NHS Accelerator Fund is a NHS Confederation-led initiative and matters relating to its development and operation are for the NHS Confederation. The Department and NHS England have not been involved in the development of this fund.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","204192","2014-07-14T13:16:20.1291701Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66096/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66096/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what fees have been paid to (a) Apposite Capital LLP, (b) The Orchard Down Consultancy Ltd, (c) Mike Farrar Consulting Ltd and (d) the NHS Confederation for their work on the NHS Accelerator Fund project.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66097","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Government has no intention of opening up National Health Service services to further competition through the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP), and this is not a focus of the negotiations. Our focus for health is to enable our world-class pharmaceutical and medical devices sectors to benefit from improved access to the United States market, increasing growth and employment in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has already undertaken long-standing agreements on trade, including in health services, since the 1995 General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATs). The UK's objective in Fair Trade Agreement negotiations, including TTIP, is to maintain commitments in health services that are broadly in line with our existing obligations under GATS. These agreements have not impacted on our ability to provide public services to date and we do not consider that TTIP will change this. As is the case now, to work or operate here any overseas healthcare professionals or companies would have to comply with UK standards and regulations, in just the same way as UK healthcare providers do.</p><p> </p><p>We have made clear to the European (EU) Commission, who is negotiating the TTIP on behalf of member states, that it must always be for member states to decide for themselves whether or not to open up public services to competition, and this is the approach that the EU Commission is taking. The TTIP should not reduce the ability of member states to make future decisions about whether and to what extent to involve the private sector in the provision of public services.</p><p> </p><p>If investment provisions are included in the TTIP, they will strike an appropriate balance between protection for UK investors abroad, and ensuring that the Government is not prevented from acting in the public interest in areas such as public health and the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to an NHS that is always there for everyone who needs it, funded from general taxation, free at the point of use. The TTIP could not change this.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-14T12:34:09.8085548Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66097/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66097/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the likely effects of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership on the National Health Service.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","204141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66098","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Local commissioners are responsible for assessing whether providers meet the prequalification criteria. NHS England has advised that the information requested is held by individual clinical commissioning groups and is not collected centrally.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T15:14:02.827322Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66098/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66098/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, further to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, columns 566-7W, on NHS: intellectual property, what returns have been made by Commissioners determining which providers have passed or failed the Commissioning for Quality and Innovation pre-qualification thresholds in 2012-13 and 2013-14 since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66099","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has advised that the next meeting of its highly specialised technology evaluation committee will take place on 24 July 2014. If the committee agrees finaldraft recommendations on eculizumab for the treatment of atypical haemolytic uraemic syndrome, NICE will aim to make them available in September in line with its interim process guide. NHS England's response will form part of the documentation published and a copy will be placed in the Library at this time.</p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-07-14T14:59:33.5164813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66099/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66099/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Haemolytic Uraemic Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, further to his Answer of 19 June 2014, Official Report, column 278W, on haemolytic uraemic syndrome, when the next meeting of the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence's evaluation committee will take place; and how soon after that meeting he expects to place a copy of NHS England's response in the Library.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen O'Brien","Eddisbury","Mr Stephen O'Brien","204175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66100","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Foreign affairs is a reserved matter. Nevertheless, the Department consults with the devolved administrations in respect of international health summits hosted by the Department. Participation in such summits is considered on a case by case basis.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-14T12:36:22.6467112Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66100/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66100/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Health Services: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what criteria he uses when considering whether to invite his counterparts from the devolved administrations to international health summits hosted by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","204176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66101","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>NHS England has advised that its review of NHS intellectual property has not yet been completed.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:46:12.4271529Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66101/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66101/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, further to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, columns 566-7W, on NHS: intellectual property, whether the Innovation, Health and Wealth board will publish the review of NHS intellectual property before 23 July 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66102","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England and has a key responsibility in the overall assurance of safety and quality of health and adult social care services.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has completed its thematic data review of diabetes care. A summary report which includes findings of the CQC's work and that of others has been shared with the Diabetes Thematic Review External Advisory Group that is supporting the project.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The CQC's plan is to publish the key national findings from this work as a short standalone report this summer.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Results from the data review will be used to inform the CQC's regular inspection regimes. The second phase will begin later in 2014 and will involve inspection activities and bespoke information gathering to follow up on the findings from the data review. It will also explore at the local level the causes behind variations in care and outcomes for different people.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","204234 ; 204236","2014-07-14T14:53:57.1721229Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66102/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66102/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress the Care Quality Commission has made in its thematic data review of diabetes care; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66103","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>No. This is a matter for Monitor as the system regulator of health services in England.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-10T15:40:56.7306165Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66103/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66103/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Christie NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will direct Monitor to publish its strategy for engaging with whistleblowers in its fact-finding investigation into alleged wrongdoing at the Christie NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","204257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66104","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England and has a key responsibility in the overall assurance of safety and quality of health and adult social care services.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has completed its thematic data review of diabetes care. A summary report which includes findings of the CQC's work and that of others has been shared with the Diabetes Thematic Review External Advisory Group that is supporting the project.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The CQC's plan is to publish the key national findings from this work as a short standalone report this summer.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Results from the data review will be used to inform the CQC's regular inspection regimes. The second phase will begin later in 2014 and will involve inspection activities and bespoke information gathering to follow up on the findings from the data review. It will also explore at the local level the causes behind variations in care and outcomes for different people.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","204234 ; 204235","2014-07-14T14:53:57.2502386Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66104/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66104/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the Care Quality Commission plans to publish its thematic data review of diabetes care.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66105","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The decision to settle a dispute with an employee is an employment matter between the Trust and the employee.</p><p> </p><p>We have written to Sir Hugh Taylor, Interim Chair of The Christie NHS Foundation Trust, informing him of this enquiry. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","204260","2014-07-10T15:34:46.1039527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66105/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66105/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Christie NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that no settlement is reached between the Christie NHS Foundation Trust and its chief executive, Caroline Shaw, on the termination of her employment until Monitor and the Care Quality Commission have concluded their current investigations into allegations of wrongdoing and published the outcome.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","204258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66106","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England and has a key responsibility in the overall assurance of safety and quality of health and adult social care services.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has completed its thematic data review of diabetes care. A summary report which includes findings of the CQC's work and that of others has been shared with the Diabetes Thematic Review External Advisory Group that is supporting the project.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The CQC's plan is to publish the key national findings from this work as a short standalone report this summer.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Results from the data review will be used to inform the CQC's regular inspection regimes. The second phase will begin later in 2014 and will involve inspection activities and bespoke information gathering to follow up on the findings from the data review. It will also explore at the local level the causes behind variations in care and outcomes for different people.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","204235 ; 204236","2014-07-14T14:53:57.062471Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66106/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66106/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how the Care Quality Commission plans to use the findings from its thematic data review of diabetes care.","true","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","204234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66107","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>These allegations were not previously known to either the Department or Ministers.</p><p> </p><p>This written question has been brought to the attention of The Christie NHS Foundation Trust, and the system regulators – in this case, Monitor, the Care Quality Commission, and the Human Tissue Authority. The regulators are best placed to deal with such concerns as they have statutory powers to take action where necessary.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-07-10T15:38:52.5727781Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66107/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Christie NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on allegations that tissue samples were sold by the Christie NHS Foundation Trust to pharmaceutical companies without the knowledge of the patients concerned; whether his attention was drawn to any such allegations; and what investigation his Department has (a) conducted and (b) plans to conduct into such allegations.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","204255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66108","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>We understand that the NHS Accelerator Fund is a NHS Confederation-led initiative and matters relating to its development and operation are for the NHS Confederation. The Department and NHS England have not been involved in the development of this fund.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","204164","2014-07-14T13:16:20.2385715Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66108/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS Accelerator Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reason the NHS Accelerator Fund and the development project were not put out to public tender.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66109","Department of Health","false","2014-07-10","<p>The National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Health Technology Assessment (HTA) programme is funding a systematic review of evidence on the benefits, harms and costs of treatments for idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.</p><p> </p><p>The researchers have sent the report of the review to the NIHR Evaluation, Trials and Studies Coordinating Centre, based at the University of Southampton, which manages the HTA programme on behalf of the Department. The report is expected to be published in the journal <em>Health Technology Assessment</em> in January 2015.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-10T15:41:39.0069204Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66109/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the National Institute for Health Research has reported to his Department the results of the research commissioned on idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","204216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66110","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>Information about National Health Service spending on bariatric surgery is not available in the format requested. Information is available from reference costs, which are the average cost to NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts for providing defined services in a given financial year to NHS patients. Reference costs for acute care are collected by Healthcare Resource Groups (HRGs), which are standard groupings of clinically similar treatments that consume common levels of healthcare resource. The HRGs in the attached table are specific to bariatric surgery and were introduced in 2011-12. For previous years, costs data is not available because the costs of bariatric surgery were included in HRGs which also covered other stomach procedures.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not undertaken an assessment of the potential benefits of bariatric surgery or evaluated its efficacy and cost-effectiveness.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has issued “Guidance on the prevention, identification, assessment and management of overweight and obesity in adults and children”. This includes recommendations on when to consider bariatric surgery for people who are obese. These recommendations were informed by an evidence review process, conducted by NICE, on the benefits and effectiveness of surgery. NICE is currently consulting on this guidance.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","204133 ; 204134","2014-07-14T12:23:42.6769033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66110/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66110/answer","PQ204132_33_34 - Table.docx","PQ204132_33_34 - Table.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","Obesity: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS spent on bariatric surgery in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","204132"
