 the Hyndburn Constituency in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","204212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66120","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Department has received no representations on this matter through its Ministerial correspondence unit during the period 1 January to 30 June 2014.</p><p> </p><p>We have received a number of questions on this subject from the hon. Member.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T13:36:49.8234448Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66120/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66120/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has received on the future of intellectual property in the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66121","Department of Health","false","2014-07-14","<p>The National Health Service's obligation to promote innovation is principally delivered through NHS England's innovation, health and wealth programme. NHS Englandreports progress on this programme to the Cabinet Office Implementation Unit, the innovation, health and wealth implementation board and the Department as part of its business plan.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-07-14T16:33:20.4987985Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66121/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66121/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-07","NHS: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2014, Official Report, column 566W, on NHS: innovation, what outputs and outcomes he uses to judge NHS England's compliance with its legal duty to promote innovation.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","204186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66122","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>In conjunction with officials from the Department for Education and the <br>Department of Health, Home Office officials are currently considering the <br>proposals submitted by the Royal College, taking into account commercial, <br>funding and value for money considerations.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:24:26.7600187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66122/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66122/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Immigrants: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Health and the Secretary of State for Education on guidance to be issued to paediatricians on age assessments of unaccompanied migrant children.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","204184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66123","Home Office","false","2014-08-06","<p>Prevent aims to stop people becoming terrorists or supporting terrorism. The revised Prevent strategy published in June 2011 has three key objectives. These are to: <br>• respond to the ideological challenge of terrorism and the threat we face from <br>those who promote it;<br>• prevent people from being drawn into terrorism and ensure that they are given <br>appropriate advice and support; and <br>• work with sectors and institutions where there are risks of radicalisation <br>which we need to address.<br>The delivery of Prevent requires strong partnerships with a range of local groups in the community, including British Muslims amongst others. <br>The Prevent strategy we inherited from the last Government was flawed. It confused the delivery of Government policy to promote integration with Government policy to prevent terrorism, which was a source of mistrust. That is why we refocused the Prevent strategy in 2011, to separate Prevent from broader integration work. <br><br>Local Prevent co-ordinators across the country work with local services, partners such as the police, Charity Commission and members of local faith communities, to understand local risks and needs, and deliver targeted projects and outreach work. We fund 30 Prevent priority areas to work on the frontline and with those vulnerable to extremism, including funding projects tailored to local needs. Prevent co-ordinators provide regular feedback to the Home Office, which helps shape the future development and implementation of the Prevent strategy. <br><br>Preventing terrorism means challenging extremist (and non-violent) ideas that are also part of a terrorist ideology. The Prevent strategy focuses on all forms of terrorism, but is clear that the most serious risk to our national security comes from Al Qa’ida, its affiliates and like-minded organisations. For this reason, the report of the Prime Minister’s Extremism Task Force (ETF), published last December, set out a definition of Islamist extremism. It noted that this ideology should not be confused with traditional religious practice. It is based on a distorted interpretation of Islam, which betrays Islam’s peaceful principles and also includes the uncompromising belief that people cannot be Muslim and British, and insists that those who do not agree with them are not true Muslims.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-08-06T10:37:55.8609961Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66123/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66123/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66123/answer/previousversion/9748","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Community Relations: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of levels of trust held by the British Muslim community in the Prevent strategy.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","204223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66124","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>I refer my Hon. Friend to my answer of 12 May 2014, Official Report, column <br>412W.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2014-07-14T12:29:19.5044951Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66124/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66124/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Riot Control Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her timetable is for the decision on the use of police water cannon in Great Britain.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","204127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66125","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p>The Department’s policy on whether to retain or destroy a file is to follow the cross-governmental guidance provided by The National Archives (TNA) where the length of retention is allocated based on legal or business requirements and historical importance. The result is that files are kept for different lengths of time depending on their content. <br><br>Those files where another government department is the policy lead or which contain minimal or duplicated content are kept for the shortest period before destruction. This period could be up to 10 years. Those which contain papers relating to issues such as legislation, major policies or notable events may be kept for up to 25 years with some files being transferred to TNA following a review of their importance in line with policy and their value for future historical research. These arrangements have been in place since 1982, with the most recent review of procedures having taken place in 2010.</p><p />","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-22T17:02:33.4987335Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66125/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66125/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Departmental Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criteria are used in her Department to decide what historic files should be (a) retained and (b) destroyed; when these criteria were established; and what reviews have been undertaken of these criteria since.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","204142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66126","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>In conjunction with officials from the Department for Education and the <br>Department of Health, Home Office officials are currently considering the <br>proposals submitted by the Royal College, taking into account commercial, <br>funding and value for money considerations.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:23:40.3195561Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66126/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66126/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Immigrants: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the proposed guidance from the Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health for paediatricians on cases of age assessment of unaccompanied migrant children.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","204179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66127","Home Office","false","2014-09-11","<p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td>£,000</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td>2011/12</td><td>2012/13</td><td>2013/14</td></tr><tr><td>Immigration System net costs</td><td>715,881</td><td>513,461</td><td>365,000</td></tr><tr><td>Asylum costs</td><td>281,365</td><td>266,773</td><td>265,183</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="4">For the immigration system net costs, we show the cost of Immigration Overseas; Border Control; Immigration In Country and Enforcement directorates.</td></tr><tr><td colspan="4">For asylum costs, we show the asylum support costs within UK Visas &amp; Immigration directorate.</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-09-11T16:42:00.0398079Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66127/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66127/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66127/answer/previousversion/9286","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of her Department's expenditure on the (a) immigration system once associated fee income has been deducted and (b) asylum system in each of the last three financial years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","204254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66128","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>A complete set of data for all litigation cases concerning age assessments of unaccompanied migrant children is not held centrally and the information requested can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-21T16:23:08.4564303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66128/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66128/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Immigrants: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many litigation cases around age assessments of unaccompanied migrant children there were in (a) 2011-12 and (b) 2012-13; and what the cost of such cases was to (i) local authorities and (ii) her Department.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","204183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66129","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>In June 2014, there were 97 referrals to the Government-funded support service <br>for adult victims of human trafficking in England and Wales administered by the <br>Salvation Army, of which 59 were female victims, 37 were male victims and 1 was <br>a transgender victim. In the interests of victim safety only the region in <br>which the victim was encountered is provided, and not the county, parliamentary <br>constituency or details of the specific shelters at which victims are <br>supported. The scope of the victim care contract does not extend (a) beyond the <br>date on which a victim exits government funded support or (b) to the safety and <br>protection of victims post the recovery and reflection period. The Salvation <br>Army therefore does not routinely maintain contact with victims outside the <br>scope of the victim care contract. <br><br>Details are provided in the table below.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T13:07:49.9890272Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66129/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66129/answer","PQ204181 Data Table.doc","PQ204181 Data Table.doc","Data -victims of human trafficking","Data -victims of human trafficking","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66129/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the nationality and gender of each suspected victim of trafficking referred to the Trafficking Victim Support Scheme operated by the Salvation Army was in June 2014 in which (a) region and (b) county each of the suspected victims was found; which agency referred each person to the Scheme; in which town the shelter was to which they were placed for the relevant period; and what contact it had with each victim after they exit the shelter to ensure they are not re-trafficked.","false","Biography information for Sir Richard Ottaway","Croydon South","Sir Richard Ottaway","204181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66130","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>The rigorous Accreditation Process applied to those participating in the <br>Commonwealth Games which contributed to the success of our Olympic Games in <br>2012 have also been central to our preparations for Glasgow 2014.<br><br>Comprehensive records checks on all Commonwealth Games participants and Games <br>Family Members are conducted before they are cleared to enter the UK. We have <br>also introduced arrangements to confirm that people given Commonwealth Games <br>clearance have left the UK within their permitted time limits.<br><br>People who visit Scotland to watch the Commonwealth Games are treated as <br>visitors to the United Kingdom and as such the normal Immigration Rules apply.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:31:38.2816457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66130/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66130/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66130/answer/previousversion/9282","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Commonwealth Games 2014","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to ensure that people who visit Scotland to participate in or watch the Commonwealth Games in 2014 are not able to remain in the country illegally after the Games have finished.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","204199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66131","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>No estimate has been made of the number of individuals who entered the UK <br>specifically to compete in the London marathon and have overstayed.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:32:35.9816045Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66131/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66131/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66131/answer/previousversion/9284","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","London Marathon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of people who have entered the UK in each of the last five years to participate in the London marathons and who remain in the country illegally; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","204205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66132","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>No estimate was made of those who overstayed in the UK after entering to <br>compete in the Paralympic Games.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:32:07.5935234Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66132/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66132/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66132/answer/previousversion/9283","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Paralympic Games 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of people who came to the UK to participate in the 2012 Paralympic Games who remain in the country illegally; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","204201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66133","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>Data for selected offences involving the use of a knife or sharp instrument are <br>collected by the Home Office at police force area level only, so data are not <br>available for Tower Hamlets or Bethnal Green and Bow constituency. Data for <br>these selected offences are in the given table for the Metropolitan Police and <br>City of London Police force areas for 2008/09 to 2012/13.<br><br>The offences covered are attempted murder, assault with injury, assault with <br>intent to cause serious harm, robbery, threats to kill, sexual assault, rape <br>and homicide. Figures for 2013/14 will be published by the Office for National <br>Statistics on 17 July 2014.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><strong>Knife and sharp instrument offences recorded by the Metropolitan and City of London police for selected offences in London<sup>1</sup>, 2008/09 to 2012/13</strong></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Numbers</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Year</strong></td><td><strong>Total selected offences <sup>2</sup></strong></td></tr><tr><td>2008/09</td><td>12,335</td></tr><tr><td>2009/10</td><td>12,620</td></tr><tr><td>2010/11</td><td>13,356</td></tr><tr><td>2011/12</td><td>14,184</td></tr><tr><td>2012/13</td><td>11,384</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2">1. Police recorded knife and sharp instrument offences data are submitted via an additional special collection. Other offences exist that are not shown in this table that may include the use of a knife or sharp instrument.</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2">2. Selected offences covered are attempted murder, assault with injury, assault with intent to cause serious harm, robbery, threats to kill, sexual assault and rape and homicide. Homicide data is taken from the Home Office Homicide Index.</td></tr></tbody></table>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-07-14T14:55:22.2368911Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66133/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66133/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Knives: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many knife-related crimes were recorded in (a) London, (b) Tower Hamlets and (c) Bethnal Green and Bow constituency in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","204172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66134","Home Office","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>Unlike special advisers who became senior officials under the last government, <br>there has been no appointment to the Home Office since 2010 of a senior civil <br>servant who was previously a political appointee within the Department. <br><br>The Department does not routinely hold the information asked in (b) therefore <br>in order to ascertain how many senior civil servants appointed since 2010 were <br>previously employed by a political party would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-15T15:27:29.1757567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66134/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66134/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many senior civil servants appointed to positions in her Department since 2010 were previously (a) political appointees within that Department and (b) employed by a political party.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66135","Home Office","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>26 recognised Civil Service professions exist across government to ensure civil <br>servants are able to develop and deliver a professional service. <br>Civil servants can find resources and information to support their professional <br>development on the Civil Service Learning portal which is accessible to all civil servants.<br><br>All professions have a head of profession; appointed for their experience, <br>knowledge and skills, who support the development of the profession and work <br>with key partners to develop timely learning curricula, which are aligned to <br>the Civil Service Competency Framework (CSCF), and civil service priorities.<br>Each of the frameworks and curricula offer a wealth of learning opportunities <br>including qualifications, workshops, and masterclasses. <br><br>Within the Home Office, opportunities for professional development are linked <br>closely with business requirements . The Home Office has 18 established <br>professions. They are: Communications, Corporate Finance, Government Economic <br>Service, Government Finance, Government IT Profession, Government Legal <br>Service, Government Property Profession, Government Social Research, Government <br>Veterinary Profession, Human Resources, Internal Audit, Knowledge and <br>Information Management, Operational Delivery, Policy Profession, Procurement, <br>Project Delivery, Science &amp; Engineering, Statistical Services.<br><br>Given the differing range of learning opportunities available for individual <br>professions, there is no single source which can identify exactly what <br>development courses are available to staff and what the cost to the public <br>purse of every professional development course is.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-17T14:08:37.0032607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66135/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66135/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what professional development courses are made available to staff of her Department; and what the cost to the public purse is of each such course.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","204346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66136","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p>In March 2014, there were 126 referrals to the Government-funded support <br>service for adult victims of human trafficking in England and Wales <br>administered by the Salvation Army, of which 78 were female victims and 48 were <br>male victims. In the interests of victim safety only the region in which the <br>victim was encountered is provided, and not the county, parliamentary <br>constituency or details of the specific shelters at which victims are <br>supported. The scope of the victim care contract does not extend (a) beyond the <br>date on which a victim exits government funded support or (b) to the safety and <br>protection of victims post the recovery and reflection period. The Salvation <br>Army therefore does not routinely maintain contact with victims outside the <br>scope of the victim care contract.<br><br>The breakdown of information requested is as follows and will be provided in <br>response to future parliamentary questions seeking equivalent information.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:28:43.5050282Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66136/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66136/answer","PQ 204316 & 204317 - Table.doc","PQ 204316 & 204317 - Table.doc","Adult victims of human trafficking","Adult victims of human trafficking","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66136/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66136/answer/previousversion/9294","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answers of 9 April 2014, Official Report, column 274WS and 14 January 2014, Official Report, column 481W, on human trafficking: victim support schemes, for what reason information on each individual and on their gender and location was not given in the former Answer; and if she will provide that information in response to future parliamentary questions seeking equivalent information.","false","Biography information for Lord Randall of Uxbridge","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Sir John Randall","204317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66137","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>There are no local understandings in place and any action is in line with the <br>Immigration Rules and Border Force Operating Mandate.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:31:01.0561902Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66137/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66137/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Fisheries: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the UK Border Force has reached any understanding with individual Scottish fishing boats regarding the employment of members of their crew who are not citizens of EEA member states.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Mr Angus Brendan MacNeil","204355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66138","Home Office","false","2014-07-14","<p> </p><p>In March 2014, there were 126 referrals to the Government-funded support <br>service for adult victims of human trafficking in England and Wales <br>administered by the Salvation Army, of which 78 were female victims and 48 were <br>male victims. In the interests of victim safety only the region in which the <br>victim was encountered is provided, and not the county, parliamentary <br>constituency or details of the specific shelters at which victims are <br>supported. The scope of the victim care contract does not extend (a) beyond the <br>date on which a victim exits government funded support or (b) to the safety and <br>protection of victims post the recovery and reflection period. The Salvation <br>Army therefore does not routinely maintain contact with victims outside the <br>scope of the victim care contract.<br><br>The breakdown of information requested is as follows and will be provided in <br>response to future parliamentary questions seeking equivalent information.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-14T12:28:04.4541989Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66138/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66138/answer","PQ 204316 & 204317 - Table.doc","PQ 204316 & 204317 - Table.doc","Adult victims of human trafficking","Adult victims of human trafficking","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66138/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/66138/answer/previousversion/9290","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-07","Human Trafficking: Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 9 April 2014, Official Report, column 274W, on human trafficking: victim support schemes, how many of those referred were (a) men and (b) women, by country; what steps are taken to ensure that after the victim exits the shelter into which they have been placed by the Salvation Army they are not retrafficked or enter contact with their former traffickers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Randall of Uxbridge","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Sir John Randall","204316"
